Yes, while directly drawing complex shapes like stars through pure HTML elements (such as divs) with CSS may not be the most straightforward approach, it can certainly be achieved with creative CSS styling, such as using borders for the lines and CSS transformations for the appropriate orientation and alignment. However, this method requires careful manipulation of the CSS properties like `transform`, `border`, and possibly `position`.

For a hollow circle, you can use a simple `div` with rounded corners and only a border. Here's a simple example to illustrate both concepts in a basic manner - drawing a hollow circle and a rough approximation of a star using HTML and CSS:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Star and Circle</title>
    <style>
        .circle {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            border-radius: 50%;
            border: 2px solid #800080;
        }
        .line {
            height: 2px;
            background-color: #800080;
            position: absolute;
            transform-origin: 0% 0%;
        }
        .line1 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(18deg); top: 40px; left: 20px; }
        .line2 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(-18deg); top: 40px; left: 20px; }
        .line3 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(54deg); top: 8px; left: 45px; }
        .line4 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(-54deg); top: 8px; right: 45px; }
        .line5 { width: 60px; top: 68px; left: 20px; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="circle"></div>
<div class="line line1"></div>
<div class="line line2"></div>
<div class="line line3"></div>
<div class="line line4"></div>
<div class="line line5"></div>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `.circle` class is used to create a hollow circle using `border-radius` and `border`. The lines of a star are simulated using the `.line` classes with specific transformations for alignment and rotation to form a very rudimentary star shape. Remember, this is a very basic representation. For more complex and accurate shapes, SVG or canvas would be preferable.

